  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_151914764" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/151914764" />
    <a title="Ian &quot;Marvin&quot; Graye" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5022264-ian-marvin-graye"><img alt="Ian &quot;Marvin&quot; Graye" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616961593p2/5022264.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/151914764?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ian &quot;Marvin&quot; Graye" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ian &quot;Marvin&quot; Graye" href="/user/show/5022264-ian-marvin-graye">Ian &quot;Marvin&quot; Graye</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5022264-ian-marvin-graye?shelf=lethem">lethem</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5022264-ian-marvin-graye?shelf=reviews">reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5022264-ian-marvin-graye?shelf=read-2021">read-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5022264-ian-marvin-graye?shelf=reviews-4-stars">reviews-4-stars</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer151914764" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1184422043075756668"><b>CRITIQUE:</b><br/><br/><b>Epigraph</b><br/><br/><i>&quot;...The subject was as easy to spot as a kangaroo in a dinner jacket.&quot;</i><br/><br/>- Raymond Chandler<br/><br/><b>The Best of Both Worlds</b><br/><br/>It&apos;s always interesting to observe a first-time author choose one or more literary worlds for their fiction, and then discover or invent a writing style that suits those worlds.<br/><br/>Here, the worlds are derived from the private detective genre of Raymond Chandler, and the near future science fiction genre of Philip K Dick. Once these choices were made, it seems that <i>&quot;Gun, Wi</i></span>
  <span id="freeText1184422043075756668" style="display:none"><b>CRITIQUE:</b><br /><br /><b>Epigraph</b><br /><br /><i>"...The subject was as easy to spot as a kangaroo in a dinner jacket."</i><br /><br />- Raymond Chandler<br /><br /><b>The Best of Both Worlds</b><br /><br />It's always interesting to observe a first-time author choose one or more literary worlds for their fiction, and then discover or invent a writing style that suits those worlds.<br /><br />Here, the worlds are derived from the private detective genre of Raymond Chandler, and the near future science fiction genre of Philip K Dick. Once these choices were made, it seems that <i>"Gun, With Occasional Music"</i> almost wrote itself, as if mechanically.<br /><br />The greatest innovation appears in the science fiction aspect of the novel, which bleeds into the private detective aspect as well. <br /><br /><b>You Can't Be Too Inquisitive</b><br /><br />Instead of a police force, San Francisco has a Grand Inquisitor's Office, which investigates and punishes crime. The inquisitors seem to have acquired a monopoly on the inquisitorial process of asking questions, even personal questions. Of course, the Office is corrupt, and is in the pocket of local gangster, Danny Phoneblum.<br /><br />Our private detective, Conrad Metcalf, is an ex-inquisitor, who has left and started his own private inquisitor business under licence (which is always precarious, because it can be suspended arbitrarily or capriciously). Although his business involves asking questions: <br /><blockquote>
  <br />
  <i>"Myself, I couldn't see myself answering all those personal questions. I'm willing to break the taboo against asking questions - in fact it's my job - but I'm pretty much like the next guy when it comes to answering them. I don't like it. That's just how it is."</i>
  <br />
</blockquote><br />Asking questions, especially personal ones, is viewed as impolite or rude. Apart from the Grand Inquisitor's Office, it doesn't pay to be curious. And the Office is skilled at turning a blind eye, except in pursuit of Conrad for illusory offences.<br /><br />Nobody knows the truth. Information and news are delivered by radio in the form of <i>"musical news",</i> which turns even news of murders into muzak or entertainment.<br /><br /><b>Karmic Playing Cards</b><br /><br />The principal tool for distributing justice (or injustice) is an electronic card from which the Office deducts karmic points, which are somehow vital to your ability to live in modern society, as if it's some sort of prepaid debit card: <br /><blockquote>
  <br />
  <i>"When the Inquisitor's Office set your card at zero, it meant you couldn't get caught slamming the door to a public rest room without sinking into a negative karmic level. The sound of that door slamming would be the last anyone heard of you for a long time, or maybe ever. I hadn't seen a card at zero for a long time, and when I had, it was always in the trembling hands of a man about to take the fall for a major aberration."</i>
  <br />
</blockquote><br />Then they put you in <i>"the freezer",</i> literally. They freeze you for the term of your sentence. You can't remember your time in the freezer when you're finally released and defrosted. It sounds worse than being exiled to Cyberia.<br /><br /><b>Drugs With Occasional Guns</b><br /><br />The other tool is officially sanctioned drugs. Even Conrad seems to be addicted to a personalised blend of drugs called <i>"make",</i> a white powder which is snorted like cocaine from a mirror or, in Conrad's case, a map of Big Sur (24). It contains patented mind-shrinking or -shaping drugs like Addictol, Avoidol, Believol, Blanketrol, Regrettol and Forgettol. You can design your own blend, give it a recipe code, and have it made at a legal <i>"makery".</i><br /><br /><b>Highly Evolved</b><br /><br />The novel refers to a process which accelerates the conversion of babies into meter high adult humans called <i>"babyheads".</i> <br /><br />Similarly, wealthy people (professionals like dentists, doctors, architects, and psychoanalysts) and gangsters have humanised pet servants who are <i>"evolved"</i> from domestic animals like apes, kittens, sheep and kangaroos (apparently inspired by the epigraph from Raymond Chandler about <i>"a kangaroo in a dinner jacket").</i> The process of <i>"evolution therapy"</i> was invented by Theodore Twostrand. <br /><br />I was tempted to ask whether babyheads dreamed of evolved sheep, but that would be rude. Besides, there was no one who could (or would) answer my question. It would also make me sound like A Dick (if not K. Dick). Honestly, I'm not yet that big a Dickhead (even if I do say so myself).<br /><br />The pet servants and babyheads introduce an element of cartoon-like unreality that detracts from the suspense and pushes the novel in the direction of political satire like <i>"Animal Farm".</i><br /><br /><b>Libido-A-Gogo and the Fickle Muse</b><br /><br />Conrad is interested in a succession of women who are at the heart of his investigation: Celeste Stanhunt, Pansey Greenleaf, and Catherine Teleprompter (an honest inquisitor). Who knows whether any of them can be trusted? Will he or they end up dead, or merely rooted? Fickle Muse isn't just the name of a bar that Danny Phoneblum controls.<br /><br />However, Conrad is libidinally compromised, mainly because an ex-girlfriend called Delia Limetree (yes, the character names sound like the work of Richard Brautigan or Kurt Vonnegut) swapped erogenous nerve endings with him, so that she could experience what it was like to be a male having sex. But Conrad has to experience what it's like to be just like a woman. Needless to say, nobody feels any pain.<br /><br /><b>Gun</b><br /><br />Just about everybody carries a gun, but Danny Phoneblum and his evolved kangaroo sidekick, Joey Castle, are the most dangerous. Needless to say more again, Joey is in the pocket of Phoneblum. Conrad does OK for a figment of the writer's imagination.<br /><br /><b>Occasional Music</b><br /><br />See the soundtrack below...<br /><br /><br /><b>EVOLVING IN RE-VERSE:</b><br /><br /><b>Black Widow Spider Barista</b><br /><br />When I first saw her<br />I wanted to play,<br />Although we didn't<br />Share much DNA.<br />The coffee she made<br />Warmed me, while the dregs<br />Kept me gazing at<br />Her furry black legs.<br /><br /><b>Reckoning</b><br /><br />I reckon<br />That you were<br />Beckoning<br />Me into<br />Bed with you.<br /><br /><b>Joey<br />[Apologies to Johnette <br />Napolitano]</b><br /><br />Joey, baby, you're so defenceless<br />Watch out for all the fences,<br />The rifles and the shooters,<br />The gangsters and the looters.<br />I'll be here if you need a pocket<br />It's safe there, don't you knock it,<br />You're my joey, you don't need a docket,<br />Here's the key, if you need to unlock it.<br /><br /><br /><b>SOUNDTRACK (OCCASIONAL MUSIC):</b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br /><b>The Vines - "Highly Evolved"</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/o15sjD2kdEw">https://youtu.be/o15sjD2kdEw</a><br /><br /><b>Robyn Hitchcock - "Ole! Tarantula"</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KtY7jwXf2QY">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KtY7j...</a><br /><br /><b>Charlotte Gainsbourg &amp; Calexico - "Just Like a Woman"</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ETBCEbMq7Ao">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ETBCE...</a><br /><br /><b>Charlotte Gainsbourg- "Just Like a Woman" ["Live" and Overdubbed]</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FNnxKr7CX1c">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FNnxK...</a><br /><br /><b>Charlotte Gainsbourg - "Hey Joe"</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ddEkj-7qA8">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ddEk...</a><br /><br /><b>Concrete Blonde - "Joey"</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OdpTcvSn8HQ">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OdpTc...</a><br /><br /><b>Concrete Blonde - "Joey" (live acoustic)</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PWCaRZhz-E0">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PWCaR...</a><br /><br /><b>Kaitlyn Schmit and The Move - "Joey" (cover)</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gf1cqoX_BXQ">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gf1cq...</a><br /><br /><b>Rolling Stones - "Beast of Burden"</b><br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/-tRdBsnX4N4">https://youtu.be/-tRdBsnX4N4</a><br /><br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="1184422043075756668" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

