    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3801643506" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3801643506" />
    <a title="Ethan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/79606570-ethan"><img alt="Ethan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1617242228p2/79606570.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3801643506?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ethan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ethan" href="/user/show/79606570-ethan">Ethan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3801643506" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15600814228458078838"><i>&quot;When in doubt, have a man come through a door with a gun in his hand.&quot;<br/><br/>- Raymond Chandler</i><br/><br/>I like Jonathan Lethem, having really enjoyed his great novel <i>Motherless Brooklyn</i>, but his quirky, doddering, pseudo-sci-fi detective novel <i>Gun, With Occasional Music</i> didn&apos;t really work for me. It follows a detective named Conrad Metcalf as he tries to solve a murder that no one else seems to care about solving, and that everyone is also seemingly trying to cover up. <br/><br/>The novel is set in a future where geneti</span>
  <span id="freeText15600814228458078838" style="display:none"><i>"When in doubt, have a man come through a door with a gun in his hand."<br /><br />- Raymond Chandler</i><br /><br />I like Jonathan Lethem, having really enjoyed his great novel <i>Motherless Brooklyn</i>, but his quirky, doddering, pseudo-sci-fi detective novel <i>Gun, With Occasional Music</i> didn't really work for me. It follows a detective named Conrad Metcalf as he tries to solve a murder that no one else seems to care about solving, and that everyone is also seemingly trying to cover up. <br /><br />The novel is set in a future where genetically-modified, sentient animals live amongst society and it's borderline illegal to ask other people questions. It makes people really uncomfortable, for whatever reason. Only certain legal authorities called "inquisitors", of which Metcalf is a lower version, are allowed to do this. The society of this book is also hopelessly dependent on drugs, constantly snorting ridiculously-named drugs like Forgettol and Addictol to keep them subservient. They've taken so much drugs that no one has any memory; people record things they need to remember into these portable "memory machines" that they then carry around. When they need to remember something, they ask their machine, and if there's no entry for it, it's just gone: people in your life, things you've done...hell, some people don't even remember where they work or where they live. The heavy drug use was something I personally didn't care for in this book. <br /><br />There are also "babyheads", which seem to be babies that were genetically modified and are now basically adults in the bodies of babies. They smoke, drink, go to speakeasy-type bars where their kind are accepted, etc. They're all really rude and aggressive (but really, everyone in this book is), and they tell jokes that are not only bad but nonsensical and just dumb, like they are all mentally-stunted or brain-damaged. They probably are. I found they grated on me as the book went on. They were off-putting, and didn't add much to the story. <br /><br />I also generally found the story was just boring. Conrad goes around, encounters someone with a gun trained on him about twenty times, talks to various people, seemingly getting nowhere, and then all of a sudden "it's six years later" and the book quickly comes to an end with the lame conclusion that the culprit was literally the most likely suspect in the entire book...not exactly a thrilling conclusion for a mystery novel. <br /><br />Can't say I'd recommend this one, other than to fans of hardboiled detective fiction or weird fiction who are looking for something off the beaten path.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15600814228458078838" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


