<div id="review_2074875139" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2074875139" />
    <a title="seb smith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1109196-seb-smith"><img alt="seb smith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567733900p2/1109196.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2074875139?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="seb smith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="seb smith" href="/user/show/1109196-seb-smith">seb smith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1109196-seb-smith?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2074875139" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4303696282574528891">I can tell when an author doesn&apos;t care about sci-fi but uses it as a setting for some edgy reason. I can also tell when an author doesn&apos;t care about women. Both are true for this book. </span>
  <span id="freeText4303696282574528891" style="display:none">I can tell when an author doesn't care about sci-fi but uses it as a setting for some edgy reason. I can also tell when an author doesn't care about women. Both are true for this book. </span>
